    {
        "type": "text",
        "text": "Please solve as many problems as you can! ",
        "bbox": [
            275,
            209,
            721,
            229
        ],
        "page_idx": 0
    },
    {
        "type": "text",
        "text": "1. (15 pts) ",
        "bbox": [
            193,
            272,
            292,
            288
        ],
        "page_idx": 0
    },
    {
        "type": "text",
        "text": "Given a finite positive (Borel) measure $d \\mu$ on [0, 1], define its sequence of moments as follows ",
        "bbox": [
            191,
            288,
            801,
            319
        ],
        "page_idx": 0
    },
    {
        "type": "equation",
        "text": "$$\nc _ {j} = \\int_ {0} ^ {1} x ^ {j} d \\mu (x), \\quad j = 0, 1, \\dots .\n$$",
        "text_format": "latex",
        "bbox": [
            356,
            323,
            640,
            361
        ],
        "page_idx": 0
    },
    {
        "type": "text",
        "text": "Show that the sequence is completely monotone in the sense that that ",
        "bbox": [
            193,
            363,
            800,
            381
        ],
        "page_idx": 0
    },
    {
        "type": "equation",
        "text": "$$\n(I - S) ^ {k} c _ {j} \\geq 0 \\quad \\mathrm {f o r a l l} j, k \\geq 0,\n$$",
        "text_format": "latex",
        "bbox": [
            357,
            385,
            638,
            405
        ],
        "page_idx": 0
    },
    {
        "type": "text",
        "text": "where $S$ denotes the backshift operator given by $S c _ { j } = c _ { j + 1 }$ for $j \\geq 0$ . ",
        "bbox": [
            193,
            407,
            800,
            426
        ],
        "page_idx": 0
    },
    {
        "type": "text",
        "text": "2. (20 pts) ",
        "bbox": [
            194,
            432,
            292,
            450
        ],
        "page_idx": 0
    },
    {
        "type": "text",
        "text": "We recall that a polynomial ",
        "bbox": [
            216,
            451,
            457,
            467
        ],
        "page_idx": 0
    },
    {
        "type": "equation",
        "text": "$$\nf (X) = a _ {d} X ^ {d} + a _ {d - 1} X ^ {d - 1} + \\dots + a _ {1} X + a _ {0} \\in \\mathbb {Z} [ X ]\n$$",
        "text_format": "latex",
        "bbox": [
            275,
            470,
            719,
            491
        ],
        "page_idx": 0
    },
    {
        "type": "text",
        "text": "is called an Eisenstein polynomial if for some prime p we have ",
        "bbox": [
            194,
            495,
            741,
            512
        ],
        "page_idx": 0
    },
    {
        "type": "list",
        "sub_type": "text",
        "list_items": [
            "(i) $p \\mid a _ { i }$ for $i = 0 , \\ldots , d - 1$ , ",
            "(ii) $p ^ { 2 } \\nmid a _ { 0 }$ ",
            "(iii) $p \\nmid a _ { d }$ "
        ],
        "bbox": [
            218,
            514,
            480,
            564
        ],
        "page_idx": 0
    },
    {
        "type": "text",
        "text": "Eisenstein polynomials are well-know to be irreducible over Z, so they can be used to construct explicit examples of irreducible polynomials. ",
        "bbox": [
            194,
            567,
            803,
            601
        ],
        "page_idx": 0
    },
    {
        "type": "text",
        "text": "Questions: ",
        "text_level": 1,
        "bbox": [
            213,
            612,
            309,
            627
        ],
        "page_idx": 0
    },
    {
        "type": "list",
        "sub_type": "text",
        "list_items": [
            "(i) Prove that a composition $f ( g ( X ) )$ of two Eisenstein polynomials $f$ and $g$ is an Eisenstein polynomial again. ",
            "(ii) Suggest a multivariate generalisation of the Eisenstein polynomials. That is, describe a class polynomials $F ( X _ { 1 } , \\ldots , X _ { m } )$ in terms of the divisibility properties of their coefficients that are guaranteed to be irreducible. "
        ],
        "bbox": [
            221,
            631,
            801,
            730
        ],
        "page_idx": 0
    },
    {
        "type": "text",
        "text": "3. (20 pts) For solving the following partial differential equation ",
        "bbox": [
            193,
            739,
            752,
            756
        ],
        "page_idx": 0
    },
    {
        "type": "equation",
        "text": "$$\nu _ {t} + f (u) _ {x} = 0, \\quad 0 \\leq x \\leq 1 \\tag {1}\n$$",
        "text_format": "latex",
        "bbox": [
            366,
            760,
            800,
            778
        ],
        "page_idx": 0
    },
    {
        "type": "text",
        "text": "where $f ^ { \\prime } ( u ) \\geq 0$ , with periodic boundary condition, we can use the following semi-discrete discontinuous Galerkin method: Find $u _ { h } ( \\cdot , t ) \\in$ $V _ { h }$ such that, for all $v \\in V _ { h }$ and $j = 1 , 2 , \\cdots , N$ , ",
        "bbox": [
            193,
            783,
            801,
            833
        ],
        "page_idx": 0
    },
    {
        "type": "equation",
        "text": "$$\n\\int_ {I _ {j}} \\left(u _ {h}\\right) _ {t} v d x - \\int_ {I _ {j}} f \\left(u _ {h}\\right) v _ {x} d x + f \\left(\\left(u _ {h}\\right) _ {j + 1 / 2} ^ {-}\\right) v _ {j + 1 / 2} ^ {-} - f \\left(\\left(u _ {h}\\right) _ {j - 1 / 2} ^ {-}\\right) v _ {j - 1 / 2} ^ {+} = 0, \\tag {2}\n$$",
        "text_format": "latex",
        "bbox": [
            194,
            838,
            801,
            890
        ],
        "page_idx": 0
    },
    {
        "type": "header",
        "text": "S.-T. Yau College Student Mathematics Contests 2014 ",
        "bbox": [
            258,
            137,
            737,
            154
        ],
        "page_idx": 0
    },
    {
        "type": "page_number",
        "text": "1 ",
        "bbox": [
            492,
            891,
            502,
            901
        ],
        "page_idx": 0
    },
    {
        "type": "text",
        "text": "with periodic boundary condition ",
        "bbox": [
            193,
            137,
            487,
            154
        ],
        "page_idx": 1
    },
    {
        "type": "equation",
        "text": "$$\n(u _ {h}) _ {1 / 2} ^ {-} = (u _ {h}) _ {N + 1 / 2} ^ {-}; \\quad (u _ {h}) _ {N + 1 / 2} ^ {+} = (u _ {h}) _ {1 / 2} ^ {+}, \\tag {3}\n$$",
        "text_format": "latex",
        "bbox": [
            315,
            160,
            800,
            180
        ],
        "page_idx": 1
    },
    {
        "type": "text",
        "text": "where $h = \\operatorname* { m a x } _ { j } ( x _ { j + 1 / 2 } - x _ { j - 1 / 2 } )$ ${ \\cal I } _ { j } \\ : = \\ : ( x _ { j - 1 / 2 } , x _ { j + 1 / 2 } )$ , $v _ { j + 1 / 2 } ^ { \\pm } = v ( x _ { j + 1 / 2 } ^ { \\pm } , t )$ , $0 = x _ { 1 / 2 } < x _ { 3 / 2 } < \\dots < x _ { N + 1 / 2 } = 1$ , and , ",
        "bbox": [
            191,
            184,
            801,
            222
        ],
        "page_idx": 1
    },
    {
        "type": "text",
        "text": "$V _ { h } = \\{ v : v | _ { I _ { j } }$ is a polynomial of degree at most $k$ for $1 \\leq j \\leq N \\}$ . ",
        "bbox": [
            211,
            225,
            784,
            244
        ],
        "page_idx": 1
    },
    {
        "type": "text",
        "text": "Prove the following $L ^ { 2 }$ stability of the scheme ",
        "bbox": [
            213,
            260,
            613,
            277
        ],
        "page_idx": 1
    },
    {
        "type": "equation",
        "text": "$$\n\\frac {d}{d t} E (t) \\leq 0 \\tag {4}\n$$",
        "text_format": "latex",
        "bbox": [
            450,
            282,
            800,
            313
        ],
        "page_idx": 1
    },
    {
        "type": "text",
        "text": "where $\\begin{array} { r } { E ( t ) = \\int _ { 0 } ^ { 1 } ( u _ { h } ( x , t ) ) ^ { 2 } d x } \\end{array}$ ",
        "bbox": [
            193,
            317,
            453,
            338
        ],
        "page_idx": 1
    },
    {
        "type": "text",
        "text": "4. Consider the linear system $A x = b$ . The GMRES method is a projection method which obtains a solution in the $m$ -th Krylov subspace $K _ { m }$ so that the residual is orthogonal to $A K _ { m }$ . Let $r _ { 0 }$ be the initial residual and let $v _ { 0 } = r _ { 0 }$ . The Arnoldi process is applied to build an orthonormal system $v _ { 1 } , v _ { 2 } , \\cdots , v _ { m - 1 }$ with $v _ { 1 } = A v _ { 0 } / \\| A v _ { 0 } \\|$ . The approximate solution is obtained from the following space ",
        "bbox": [
            191,
            344,
            801,
            445
        ],
        "page_idx": 1
    },
    {
        "type": "equation",
        "text": "$$\nK _ {m} = \\operatorname {s p a n} \\left\\{v _ {0}, v _ {1}, \\dots , v _ {m - 1} \\right\\}.\n$$",
        "text_format": "latex",
        "bbox": [
            371,
            451,
            626,
            468
        ],
        "page_idx": 1
    },
    {
        "type": "text",
        "text": "(i) (5 points) Show that the approximate solution is obtained as the solution of a least-square problem, and that this problem is triangular. ",
        "bbox": [
            226,
            472,
            801,
            521
        ],
        "page_idx": 1
    },
    {
        "type": "list",
        "sub_type": "text",
        "list_items": [
            "(ii) (5 points) Prove that the residual $r _ { k }$ is orthogonal to $\\{ v _ { 1 } , v _ { 2 } , \\cdots , v _ { k - 1 } \\}$ ",
            "(iii) (5 points) Find a formula for the residual norm. ",
            "(iv) (5 points) Derive the complete algorithm. "
        ],
        "bbox": [
            218,
            521,
            853,
            573
        ],
        "page_idx": 1
    },
    {
        "type": "text",
        "text": "5. (10 pts) ",
        "bbox": [
            193,
            580,
            290,
            598
        ],
        "page_idx": 1
    },
    {
        "type": "text",
        "text": "(i) Set $x _ { 0 } = 0$ . Write the recurrence ",
        "bbox": [
            228,
            600,
            544,
            615
        ],
        "page_idx": 1
    },
    {
        "type": "equation",
        "text": "$$\nx _ {k} = 2 x _ {k - 1} + b _ {k}, \\quad k = 1, 2, \\dots , n,\n$$",
        "text_format": "latex",
        "bbox": [
            351,
            624,
            647,
            639
        ],
        "page_idx": 1
    },
    {
        "type": "text",
        "text": "in a matrix form $A { \\overrightarrow { x } } = { \\overrightarrow { b } }$ . For $b _ { 1 } = - 1 / 3$ , $b _ { k } = ( - 1 ) ^ { k } , k =$ $2 , 3 , \\cdots , n$ , verify that $x _ { k } \\ = \\ ( - 1 ) ^ { k } / 3 , k \\ = \\ 1 , 2 , \\cdot \\cdot \\cdot , n$ is the exact solution. ",
        "bbox": [
            255,
            645,
            801,
            694
        ],
        "page_idx": 1
    },
    {
        "type": "text",
        "text": "(ii) Find $A ^ { - 1 }$ and compute condition number of $A$ in $L ^ { 1 }$ norm. ",
        "bbox": [
